          <h3>Introduction</h3>

          <p>Sexual violence on campuses is certainly not a new problem. It is unfortunately pervasive. More than one in ten university students will experience some form of sexual violence during their time at school. (https://www.rainn.org/statistics/campus-sexual-violence) </p>

          <p>This topic is especially important in light of the recent developments at BYU concerning Title IX. &ldquo;In May 2016, BYU President Kevin J Worthen organized the Advisory Council on Campus Response to Sexual Assault with a charge to identify changes that will help BYU work toward the elimination of sexual assault on campus&rdquo; (https://news.byu.edu/title-ix). Hearing the heartbreaking experiences of our fellow students urged us to consider this prevalent issue.
            Our goal was to build strong enough models that would allow us to
            be able to predict sexual assault on college campuses. </p>

          <p>We chose to limit the scope of our project to colleges and universities in the United States, to avoid any skewing of the data due to different cultures in other countries. We also chose to exclude two-year, for-profit universities for two reasons: the nature of the institution is fundamentally different from other institutions (being for-profit), and we had reason to believe that the reporting of for-profit schools was less accurate than other institutions. </p>

          <p>After researching for reputable data sources, the best and most complete data we could find was concerning crimes on college campuses. We chose to focus our efforts on discovering whether and how the following factors affect sexual crimes: enrollment (total and men vs. women), other crimes (i.e. arson, robbery, etc.) and corresponding city population. Due to time constraints and unavailability of data we regretfully were unable to explore countless other factors that may or may not contribute to issues of sexual violence. </p>

          <p>We hope that our work will be able to provide insights into what could contribute to or affect &ldquo;rape culture&rdquo; at a given institution, or campuses in the US in general. Our goal is to aid administrators and law enforcement in drafting and enacting policy changes to make positive progress.</p>

