          <h3>Report & Findings</h3>
          <p>Negligent manslaughter, murder, and weapons related crimes have almost no correlation to Sexual Assaults. This makes sense statistically in light of the scarcity of these crimes, and logically we also can draw conclusions that if there is a murder then the odds of sexual assault should not necessarily be affected. Negligent manslaughter refers to an unintentional killing that results from recklessness or criminal negligence, or from an unlawful act that is a misdemeanor or low-level felony (such as a DUI). This also does not lend itself to prediction of sexual crimes. Arson is another crime that similarly holds very little predictive capabilities in regards to sexual assault.</p>

          <p>Men and women totals were very predictive columns, which makes sense because the most common situation in which sexual assaults occur is between a man and a woman (https://sapac.umich.edu/article/196). From a policy standpoint this information is valuable, but not extremely useful in the formulation of prevention policy, because you cannot simply remove one or the other gender. </p>

          <p>One column that we thought would hold more predictive power than what the data actually proved was population. One of our early suppositions was that areas with higher population would have higher crime, and thus higher incidences of sexual assault. This line of thinking turned out to be fallacious, as the data went on to show in almost all algorithms, that the population of the city where a school is based has little to do with the amount of sexual assaults that will transpire there. </p>

          <p>In contrast with population, the type of university you are at actually does seem to be aligned with the number of sexual assaults that will happen. We predicted that this would be the case, and the data proved us right. Whether you are at a 4-year for profit institution, or a 2-year non-profit institution actually can make a difference in the number of sexual assaults. VisMiner identified liquor violations as one of the most predictive variables, which was very significant to us. We also believed prior to running any algorithms on the data that liquor would be tied to the number of sexual assaults. This is very important from a policy standpoint and is our biggest takeaway from this entire process. Liquor violations are very related to the number of sexual assaults that occur on a campus. This is very useful to any administration who is looking to lower incidences of sexual assault. They now can see what is affecting sexual assaults, and can make decisions and policies that work towards limiting the assaults. Removing liquor from campuses, or even being more strict with liquor rules could have huge results for any university that decides to implement these policies.</p>

          <p>We are confident in our results because of how we prepared the data, the number of algorithms we ran on the data, and the predictions and correlations we can see because of the algorithms we used. We believe this data will be useful to many administrators as they move towards limiting sexual crimes. If they work on limiting alcohol violations, they will also be able to limit sexual assaults. This is our goal, and the data shows a way that we can achieve it. </p>

